Starbucks Customer Reviews: NLP and Sentiment Analysis

Background:

This dataset contains a comprehensive collection of consumer reviews and ratings for Starbucks, a renowned coffeehouse chain. The data was collected through web scraping and includes textual reviews, star ratings, location information, and image links from multiple pages on the ConsumerAffairs website. It offers valuable insights into customer sentiment and feedback about Starbucks locations.

Objective :

To analyze customer sentiment in online reviews of Starbucks locations and products.

Import Libraries

library(tm)
library(sentimentr)
library(tidyverse)
library(wordcloud)

Analysis Steps:

  1. Text Pre-processing
  2. Creation of WordCloud
  3. Sentiment Analysis - By Year

1) Text Pre-processing

# Convert Reviews to lowercase.
data$Cleaned_Review <- tolower(data$Review) 

# Remove stop words like: i, me, our and, the, is, etc.
data$Cleaned_Review <- removeWords(data$Cleaned_Review, stopwords("en")) 

# Remove all characters(#$",@, etc.) except alphabets, numbers, and spaces.
data$Cleaned_Review <- gsub("[^[:alnum:][:space:]]", "", data$Cleaned_Review) 

# Remove numbers from the text
data$Cleaned_Review <- gsub("[0-9]", "", data$Cleaned_Review)

# Remove words that are obvious
data$Cleaned_Review <- removeWords(data$Cleaned_Review, c("drinks", "starbucks", "coffee", "order", "cafe")) 

#Remove any leading or trailing whitespace and Reduce sequence of whitespace to a single space.
data$Cleaned_Review <- str_squish(data$Cleaned_Review)

2) Creating Word Clouds from Text and Visualizing Reviews

Based on the Rating column we will plot two Word clouds as follows:

  1. Reviews for customers with rating > 3

  2. Reviews for customers with rating < 3

Here, Rating = 3, is neutral

# The code filters data for reviews with Ratings above 3, extracts words from Cleaned_Review column, counts their occurrences, and sorts them by frequency.
positive_reviews <-subset(data,Rating>3)
positive_reviews <- positive_reviews %>%
  dplyr::select(Cleaned_Review) %>%
  tidytext::unnest_tokens(word, Cleaned_Review) %>%
  dplyr::count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

# Word cloud for Negative Reviews:
wordcloud(negative_reviews$word, negative_reviews$n, random.order = FALSE, min.freq =1, scale=c(3,.3), colors=pal)

3) Calculating Sentiment Scores

The sentiment() function from sentimentr package analyzes text and computes a sentiment score for each entry, which is then stored. The resulting score represents the overall sentiment or sentiment polarity of each text entry in the dataset. A positive score typically indicates a positive sentiment in the text, while a negative score suggests a negative sentiment, with the magnitude of the score indicating the strength of the sentiment.
#Perform sentiment analysis on the cleaned reviews.
data$Compound_Score<-sentiment(data$Cleaned_Review)$sentiment

Analyzing Sentiment Trends (Compound Score) Over Recent Years

# Extracting Year from Date column. 
# str_split will split "Sept 13, 2023" into Sept 13 and 2023, we will need the 2nd half hence, x[[2]]
data$Year <- str_split(data$Date, ", ") %>% sapply(function(x) x[[2]]) 
data$Year<-as.numeric(data$Year)
recentdata <- subset(data,Year > 2018)

mean_scores_by_year <-recentdata %>% group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(`Compound Score`= mean(Compound_Score))

ggplot(data = mean_scores_by_year, aes(x = Year, y = `Compound Score`, fill = as.factor(Year))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
  labs(title = "Mean Compound Score by Year (Year > 2018)",x = "Year",y = "Mean Compound Score",fill="Year") +
  theme_minimal()

Observations :

- There is some variation in the compound sentiment scores across the years, with 2021 and 2022 showing the highest mean compound score and 2019 showing the lowest. This indicates potential fluctuations in sentiment in different years.
